{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ff4f80b0-f1ea-42a0-9647-d6553da4435a","content":"In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are gone. Instead, use **`Window` lifecycle events**. Override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class and return a custom `Window`, or subclass `Window` and override its methods:\n\n| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI Window |\n|---------------|------------------|\n| `OnStart` | `OnCreated()` |\n| `OnSleep` | `OnStopped()` |\n| `OnResume` | `OnResumed()` |\n\n**Example:**\n\n```csharp\npublic partial class App : Application\n{\n    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n    {\n        var window = new Window(new AppShell());\n\n        window.Created += (s, e) => { /* OnStart equivalent */ };\n        window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep equivalent */ };\n        window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* OnResume equivalent */ };\n\n        return window;\n    }\n}\n```\n\nOr subclass `Window` directly:\n\n```csharp\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated() { /* ... */ base.OnCreated(); }\n    protected override void OnStopped() { /* ... */ base.OnStopped(); }\n    protected override void OnResumed() { /* ... */ base.OnResumed(); }\n}\n```\n\nFor platform-specific hooks, use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1b8c7b89-1912-4bd1-86ef-21a812ae9a34","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a straightforward knowledge question about the MAUI lifecycle API.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` in your `Application` class. In .NET MAUI, the lifecycle model changed. You now use the `Window` lifecycle events or the cross-platform lifecycle events through the `ILifecycleBuilder` in `MauiProgram.cs`, or you can override `CreateWindow` and hook into `Window` events.\n\nActually, let me be more precise:\n\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the `Application` class no longer has `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, or `OnResume`. Instead, you override lifecycle methods on the `Window` class—`OnCreated()` maps to the old `OnStart`, and there are corresponding methods for the other lifecycle states. You can either override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class to customize the window and subscribe to its events, or create a custom `Window` subclass with overridden lifecycle methods.","outputTokens":783,"requestId":"A852:1918B9:67FD38:786CF1:69FBE374"},"id":"ff8602d9-c71a-4a87-b0d2-94fcca53611c","timestamp":"2026-05-07T00:57:40.539Z","parentId":"56ae625f-046b-4205-8179-e0e81fa2bbb0"}
